item.title: [Showoff} Arcanian Scythe
item.dc:creator: @davidi2 Davidi2
item.description:
@davidi2 wrote:

You missed my point. I probably said it in a confusing way. But here is what I meant:

He did not use a cuboid and bend it from scratch into that shape. He had traced the model and just filled in the trace with the cuboid. If you know what this means:

coloring : staying inside lines :: modeling : filling in a trace

How do I know? I have made models for my clients with tracing, but I do not post them here because I know it is retarded to just post something I traced and filled in.

Read full topic

We need more guys like you, I see you done some real primitive modelling in the handle, unlike most of the stuff here which is just scaled down cylinders, aha, amazing job.
[/quote]
He didn’t do any real primative modeling.[/quote]

Who’s the experienced modeller here?
Who’s been doing it for nearly 2 years?

That handle is a segmented cuboid bent into several different angles using the move tool, yes, it sounds simple, it is, but it’s the most primitive modelling I’ve seen in this section besides dylan so far.

item.dc:creator: @SilentCJ SilentCJ
item.description:
@SilentCJ wrote:

Davidi2:

Well I think it is rather immature to be making people think you spend a lot of time “making” models (look it up in a dictionary), when you are tracing them.

Leave him alone, gawdddd.
It’s still making them, it’s just another method of modelling.

This is kinda a bad example, but it’s like, primitive modelling is like building a house with your hands, and trace modelling is like building it using machinery and cranes and whatnot. It still gets the job done, but it may not be as good as the hand crafted work, but is quicker, and it was still made by that person.

Shitty example, I know. :rolleyes:
